               <p>EDWARD LANDER. I am a <rs id="t18300415-63-viclabel352" type="occupation">shoemaker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-63-victim681 t18300415-63-viclabel352"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18300415-63-crimeloc353">Great Queen-street, Lincoln's Inn-fields</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-63-crimeloc353" type="placeName" value="Great Queen-street, Lincoln's Inn-fields"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-63-crimeloc353" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-63-off350 t18300415-63-crimeloc353"></join>. The prisoner came to my shop alone, about ten o'clock on the morning of the 18th of March; he asked for a light pair of shoes I showed him a pair; he said they were not wide enough- I turned to give him a pair from the shelf, and while I was turning he took this pair, which were cleaned, on the counter, ready to go home; when I turned back he said his brother was at the door, and he would call in againjust then the person these shoes were for, came for them; I sent my boy for the prisoner, who brought him back.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-63-person682">
                  JOHN 
                  HUNT
               <interp inst="t18300415-63-person682" type="surname" value="HUNT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-63-person682" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-63-person682" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I went after the prisoner, who had got about nine doors from the house; I said he had a pair of my master's shoes - I cannot tell what he said, but I saw<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183004150044"></xptr>the shoes under his coat; I called my master, who came, and the prisoner threw the shoes up in a corner.</p>
